  "prompt": "What does it mean when your left eye twitches?",
  "response": "The twitching of the left eye, also known as *myokymia*, is typically a benign and temporary condition. It is usually caused by minor issues such as:\n\n1. **Fatigue or Sleep Deprivation**: Lack of rest can strain the muscles around the eye, leading to twitching.\n2. **Stress or Anxiety**: High stress levels can trigger muscle tension, including in the eye area.\n3. **Caffeine or Alcohol**: Excessive consumption of these substances can stimulate the nervous system and cause twitching.\n4. **Eye Strain**: Prolonged use of screens, reading, or focusing on small details can tire the eye muscles.\n5. **Dry Eyes**: Insufficient lubrication of the eye can cause irritation and twitching.\n6. **Nutritional Imbalance**: A deficiency in vitamins like magnesium or B12 can lead to muscle spasms.\n7. **Allergies**: Eye irritation from allergies can cause twitching.\n\nIn most cases, eye twitching resolves on its own with rest, stress reduction, and proper hydration. However, if the twitching persists for more than a few weeks, is severe, or affects other parts of the face, it may be a sign of an underlying neurological condition, such as **blepharospasm** or **hemifacial spasm**, and you should consult a healthcare professional for evaluation.\n\nIn some cultures, a left eye twitch is believed to have spiritual or superstitious meanings, such as impending good or bad luck, but these interpretations are not scientifically supported.",
